[start section id="20112"]

#1 Rule-out gastrointestinal bleeding
Mr. Newsome's history of having melena almost on a daily basis and associated with a prior history of a left hemicolectomy (April 26) for a T3, N0, MX adenocarcinoma of the colon is concerning.  In addition to this, the patient has orthostasis.  His bradycardia is most likely related to the ongoing use of beta-blockers.  He also has abdominal distention.  Some symptoms to me are concerning for gastric outlet obstruction.  The patient reports having minimal oral intake; and even after minimal meals, he has abdominal distention, nausea; and all of the symptoms are relieved by the patient having an episode of vomiting.  I discussed with Mr. Newsome and his two daughters that at this point my recommendation for him is to be evaluated at the ER for evaluation for potential admission.  His main issues are his ongoing GI bleeding as well as the symptoms of gastric outlet obstruction.  He is also status-post a left hemicolectomy and has also an unresectable urothelial carcinoma.  He also has indeterminate liver lesions that to me are concerning for being metastases from his urothelial cancer.  I had discussed in the past with Mr. Newsome that he is not a surgical candidate for his urothelial cancer and that if any treatment is going to be done will require the patient to have a better performance status.  In the current condition, the patient is not a candidate for active treatment with chemotherapy.  I have referred the patient for evaluation at ER.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at Haven House Hospital.

